AGREED TERMS
Parties and background

This Master Services Agreement (the Agreement) is entered into between the Supplier (as defined above in the Agreement Details) and PRINSIX TECHNOLOGIES LIMITED incorporated and registered in England and Wales with company number 12315496 whose registered office is at 4 Wharfe Mews, Cliffe Terrace, Wetherby, West Yorkshire, LS22 6LX (the Customer).
This Agreement operates as a master services agreement, which allows the parties to enter into one or more Statements of Work for Services.
The parties may agree any number of Statements of Work under the terms of this Agreement following the process set out in the MSA Terms and Conditions of Purchase in Schedule 2.
Scope of the Agreement

The Schedules form part of this Agreement and shall have effect as if set out in full in the body of this Agreement. Any reference to this Agreement includes the Schedules except where required or implied by the context or where expressly stated.

Where the Statement of Work in Schedule 1 specifies Services (the Initial Services), that Schedule and the relevant information in the Agreement Details shall together form the first Statement of Work.

The parties may agree any number of Statements of Work for Services, each of which shall be substantially in the form set out in Schedule 1.  Each Statement of Work shall be deemed to be a Schedule to this Agreement when it is signed by the authorised representatives of both parties.
At the date this Agreement is signed by the parties, the Schedules are as follows:
Schedule 1: Statement of Work for the Initial Services / Template Statement of Work.
Schedule 2: the MSA Terms and Conditions of Purchase which shall apply to the Agreement, including all Statements of Work.
Schedule 3: Data Protection.
Commencement and duration

This Agreement shall commence on the date specified above and shall continue for an initial period of 12 months (the “Initial Term”), unless terminated earlier in accordance with section 14 of the MSA Terms and Conditions of Purchase (Termination).

Following expiry of the Initial Term, the Agreement shall automatically renew for successive periods of 12 months (each a “Renewal Term”) unless either party gives the other written notice of its intention to terminate the Agreement, such notice to be received no later than 30 days prior to the end of the Initial Term or the relevant Renewal Term, as applicable, in which case:
if the Services under all Statements of Work have been completed at that date, the Agreement shall terminate at the end of the Initial Term or the relevant Renewal Term, as applicable; whereas

if any Services under any Statements of Work have not been completed at that date, the Agreement shall continue to apply to such Statements of Work until they have been completed, as described in section 15 of the MSA Terms and Conditions of Purchase.
The commencement, duration and renewal terms of any Services agreed under a Statement of Work shall be as set out in the Statement of Work.

Interpretation
The following definitions and rules of interpretation apply in these Terms and Conditions:

Agreement: the agreement between the parties consisting of the Master Services Agreement and its Schedules (including these MSA Terms and Conditions of Purchase and any Statements of Work agreed by the parties under the Agreement).
Applicable Laws: all applicable laws, statutes and regulation from time to time in force.
Business Day: a day, other than a Saturday, Sunday or public holiday in England, when banks in London are open for business.
Charges: the sums payable for the Services as set out in the Statement of Work.
control: has the meaning given in section 1124 of the Corporation Tax Act 2010, and the expression change of control shall be construed accordingly.
Marks: has the meaning given in section 8.8.

Customer Materials: all documents, information, items and materials in any form, whether owned by the Customer or a third party, which are provided or made available to the Supplier in connection with the Services.
Customer Systems: means the Customer’s or any third party’s network(s) and information technology system(s) which are used directly or indirectly by the Supplier in connection with the Services.

Deliverables: any outputs of the Services to be provided by the Supplier to the Customer or, where relevant, any Service Recipient(s) as specified in a Statement of Work and any other documents, products and materials provided by the Supplier to the Customer or, where relevant, any Service Recipient(s) in relation to the Services.

Intellectual Property Rights: patents, rights to inventions, copyright and related rights, trade marks, business names and domain names, rights in get-up, goodwill and the right to sue for passing off, rights in designs, rights in computer software, database rights, rights to use, and protect the confidentiality of, confidential information (including know-how and trade secrets) and all other intellectual property rights, in each case whether registered or unregistered and including all applications and rights to apply for and be granted, renewals or extensions of, and rights to claim priority from, such rights and all similar or equivalent rights or forms of protection which subsist or will subsist now or in the future in any part of the world.
Key Personnel: the individuals identified as key personnel in a Statement of Work, or any replacement individuals appointed by the Supplier pursuant to section 4.

Service Recipient: where relevant, any third party who is the intended beneficiary of some or all of the Services and/or the Deliverables under the Statement of Work, as set out in the Statement of Work or as communicated by the Customer from time to time.
Services: the services to be provided by the Supplier as set out in the Statement of Work.
Services Start Date: the commencement date the Services, as set out in the Statement of Work, or if no such date is specified, the date the Statement of Work is agreed by the parties.
Statement of Work: a statement of work agreed and signed by both parties, setting out a description of the relevant Services, Charges and any other material terms.
Supplier Personnel: any individuals involved in providing the Services, including any substitutes
Terms and Conditions: these MSA Terms and Conditions of Purchase
Third Party Material: any material included in the Deliverables the rights in which are not owned by the Customer, any Service Recipient(s) or the Supplier.
VAT: value added tax or any equivalent tax chargeable in the UK or elsewhere.
Clause, Schedule, section and paragraph headings shall not affect the interpretation of these Terms and Conditions or the Agreement.
A person includes a natural person, corporate or unincorporated body (whether or not having separate legal personality).
A reference to a company shall include any company, corporation or other body corporate, wherever and however incorporated or established.

The Agreement shall be binding on, and enure to the benefit of, the parties to the Agreement and their respective personal representatives, successors and permitted assigns, and references to any party shall include that party’s personal representatives, successors and permitted assigns.

A reference to legislation or a legislative provision is a reference to it as amended, extended or re-enacted from time to time and shall include all subordinate legislation made from time to time under that legislation or legislative provision.
A reference to writing or written includes email.
Any obligation on a party not to do something includes an obligation not to allow that thing to be done.

References to clauses and Schedules are to the clauses and Schedules of the Agreement, references to sections are to the sections of these Terms and Conditions and references to paragraphs are to paragraphs of the relevant Schedule.

Any words following the terms including, include, in particular, for example or any similar expression shall be construed as illustrative and shall not limit the sense of the words, description, definition, phrase or term preceding those terms.
Statements of Work
Each Statement of Work shall be agreed by the parties in writing.
No party is obliged to agree any Statements of Work.

No Statement of Work shall be effective unless it is signed by the authorised representatives of both parties or forms part of an agreement which is signed by the authorised representatives of both parties.

Any terms included, or referred to, in any quotation for services provided by the Supplier and any other terms provided or referred to by the Supplier which are not expressly incorporated into the signed Statement of Work are excluded from the Statement of Work and this Agreement.

Once a Statement of Work is effective, any amendments or variations to the Statement of Work must be agreed in writing and signed by the parties.  The parties acknowledge that any change to the specification of Services may result in changes to the relevant Charges.
All Statements of Work shall be interpreted and performed by the parties in accordance with the terms of the Agreement and shall be considered to form part of the Agreement.
Each Statement of Work shall be part of the Agreement and shall not form a separate contract to it.
Supplier’s responsibilities
The Supplier shall:
provide the Services and the Deliverables in accordance with the relevant Statement(s) of Work and in a form satisfactory to the Customer, acting reasonably.

ensure that the Services and Deliverables will conform in all respects with the Statement of Work and that the Deliverables shall be fit for any purpose expressly or implicitly made known to the Supplier by the Customer or, where relevant, any Service Recipient(s);
provide the Services in accordance with the timetable set out in the Statement of Work and with all reasonable care, attention and skill;
provide all equipment, tools, vehicles and other items required to provide the Services;

co-operate with the Customer’s and, where relevant, any Service Recipient’s employees, officers and agents in all matters relating to the Services and comply with all reasonable and lawful instructions of the Customer and, where relevant, any Service Recipient(s);
comply with all applicable laws, statutes, regulations and any applicable Customer policies and codes of practice;
provide the Services at such locations as are set out in the Statement of Work or as may be reasonably required by the Customer;
observe all health and safety rules and regulations and any other reasonable security requirements that apply at any of Customer’s premises;

hold all Customer Materials in safe custody at its own risk, maintain such Customer Materials in good condition until returned to the Customer or, where relevant, the Service Recipient, and not dispose of or use the Customer Materials other than in accordance with the Customer's or, where relevant, the Service Recipient’s written instructions or authorisations;
not access or use any Customer Systems in any way or for any purpose which is not authorised by the Customer or the relevant Service Recipient;
ensure that all Deliverables prepared or stored by the Supplier pursuant to the Statement of Work are stored or delivered securely;

not do or omit to do anything which may cause the Customer or, where relevant, any Service Recipient to lose any licence, authority, consent or permission on which it relies for the purposes of conducting its business;
notify the Customer in writing immediately upon the occurrence of a change of control of the Supplier; and
comply with any additional obligations imposed on it as set out in a Statement of Work.
Unless otherwise agreed, failure to meet a performance date specified in the Statement of Work shall constitute a material breach.

If, in the reasonable opinion of the Customer or any Service Recipient(s), the Supplier does not provide the Services (or any part of them) in accordance with the Statement of Work, the Customer may, at its option and without prejudice to any other rights and remedies the Customer may have, require the Supplier to remedy matters at the Supplier's own cost and expense, in which case:
no Charges shall be due in respect of the Services in question until matters have been remedied; and

the Charges due once matters have been remedied shall not exceed the Charges that would have been payable had the Services in question been provided initially in accordance with the Statement of Work.
Supplier Personnel
In relation to the Supplier Personnel, the Supplier shall:
use the Key Personnel in the provision of the Services;

ensure that all Supplier Personnel have suitable skills and experience to enable them to perform the tasks assigned to them, and that such Supplier Personnel are in sufficient number to enable the Supplier to fulfil its obligations under this agreement; and
promptly inform the Customer of the absence (or the anticipated absence) of any of the Key Personnel, and if so required by the Customer, provide a suitably qualified replacement for such individual.

The Supplier may, subject to the following provisos, by way of written notice to the Customer appoint an equally qualified and skilled substitute for any Key Personnel, able to perform the Services, provided that the Customer reserves the right to veto the Supplier's choice of substitute if the Customer or, where relevant, any Service Recipient reasonably believes them not to be suitably qualified, skilled or able to perform the Services in question. in accordance with the terms of the Statement of Work.
The Supplier shall:
be responsible for the remuneration of any Supplier Personnel;
procure that all Supplier Personnel act in accordance with the Supplier’s obligations under the Agreement;
be responsible for all acts and omissions of any Supplier Personnel, as though those were the acts and omissions of the Supplier; and

where required by the Customer and/or, where relevant, any Service Recipient(s) procure that any Supplier Personnel enter into direct undertakings with the Customer and/or such Service Recipient(s), including with regard to confidentiality and intellectual property.
Service Recipients

Where the Services involve the Supplier interacting with any Service Recipient(s) on behalf of the Customer or providing Services and/or Deliverables some or all of which are for the benefit of any Service Recipient(s):
the references to “Customer” in sections 3.2(d) to 3.2(g) [OTHERS] shall be deemed to include such Service Recipient(s);

the Supplier shall indemnify the Customer in full against all liabilities, costs, expenses, damages and losses (including any direct, indirect or consequential losses, loss of profit, loss of reputation and all interest, penalties and legal costs (calculated on a full indemnity basis) and all other professional costs and expenses) suffered or incurred by the Customer arising out of or in connection with any claim brought against the Customer by any Service Recipient(s) or any third-party arising out of, or in connection with, any breach.

Customer’s obligations

Charges and payment
In consideration of the provision of the Services by the Supplier, the Customer shall pay the Charges set out in the Statement of Work.

The Supplier shall invoice the Customer for the Charges at the intervals specified or on the achievement of the milestones indicated in the Statement of Work (which may include acceptance by the Customer, or any Service Recipient(s), of a particular Deliverable).  If no intervals or milestones are specified, the Supplier shall invoice the Customer on acceptance by the Customer, or any Service Recipient(s), of the last of the Deliverables due under the relevant Statement of Work.
Each invoice shall include such supporting information as the Customer requires to verify the accuracy and validity of the invoice.
The Customer shall pay each valid invoice submitted to it by the Supplier within 30 days of receipt by the Customer.
All sums payable to the Supplier under the Agreement:
are exclusive of VAT, and the Customer shall in addition pay an amount equal to any VAT chargeable on those sums on delivery of a VAT invoice; and
shall be paid in full without any set-off, counterclaim, deduction or withholding (other than any deduction or withholding of tax as required by law).

Without prejudice to any other right or remedy that it may have, if the Customer fails to pay the Supplier any sum due under the Agreement on the due date the Customer shall pay interest on the overdue sum from the due date until payment of the overdue sum, whether before or after judgment. Interest will accrue each day at 4% a year above the Bank of England's base rate from time to time, but at 4% a year for any period when that base rate is below 0%.

The Customer may, at any time, without notice to the Supplier, set off any liability of the Supplier to the Customer against any liability of the Customer to the Supplier, whether either liability is present or future, liquidated or unliquidated, and whether or not either liability arises under the Agreement. Any exercise by the Customer of its rights under this clause shall not limit or affect any other rights or remedies available to it under this agreement or otherwise.

The Customer shall reimburse any reasonable costs or expenses incurred by the Supplier in providing the Services, provided such costs or expenses were agreed in writing in advance by the Customer and subject to the Supplier’s production of appropriate supporting documentation.
Intellectual property rights
The provisions of this section 8 are subject to any variations expressly set out in the Statement of Work.

Title to any Deliverables that are goods or in any physical media on which Deliverables are stored shall pass to the Customer on the earlier of their delivery to the Customer or any Service Recipient(s) or payment of the Charges for them.  The Supplier warrants that it has full, clear and unencumbered title to all such items, and that at the date of the transfer of title, it shall have full and unrestricted rights to transfer all such items to the Customer.

The Supplier assigns to the Customer, with full title guarantee and free from all third-party rights (by way of present and future assignment) all Intellectual Property Rights in the Deliverables, other than the Third Party Materials referred to in section 8.6.

If requested to do so, the Supplier agrees to execute (and, if relevant, to procure that any Supplier Personnel executes) such deeds and documents and do such other acts as the Customer may reasonably require to perfect the assignment of the relevant Intellectual Property Rights.

The Supplier hereby irrevocably waives, and warrants and undertakes to the Customer that they will obtain from any Supplier Personnel a written irrevocable waiver of, in respect of the Deliverables (other than the Third Party Materials referred to in section 8.6) and to the fullest extent permissible by law, any and all statutory moral rights to which they may now or at any future time be entitled anywhere in the world.  The Supplier agrees to provide to the Customer a copy of the waiver on request.
The Supplier may use existing third-party copyright material in the creation of the Deliverables provided that:
the Supplier has obtained the Customer’s prior agreement in writing and the Customer has agreed the cost; and
the owner of the material has given the Customer and/or any Service Recipient(s) permission for such uses as required under the Statement of Work.
In relation to the Customer Materials:
the Customer and its licensors and, where relevant, any Service Recipient and its licensors shall retain ownership of all Intellectual Property Rights in the Customer Materials;

the Customer grants the Supplier a non-exclusive, royalty-free, non-transferable licence to copy and modify any Customer Materials provided by the Customer for the term of the relevant Statement(s) of Works for the purpose of providing the Services;
the Supplier agrees that it shall not use any Customer Materials for any purpose which is not authorised by the Customer or, where relevant, any Service Recipient; and
except as expressly stated herein or in the Statement of Work the Supplier shall not acquire any right, title or interest in or to the Customer Material.

The Supplier shall not use any trade marks, branding and/or trade names of the Customer or any Service Recipient(s) (“Marks”) except as expressly authorised by the Customer or the Service Recipient(s), as relevant.  Unless expressly agreed otherwise in writing, such licence shall be non-exclusive, non-transferable and revocable by the Customer.
The Supplier:

warrants that the receipt, use and onward supply of the Services and the Deliverables by the Customer or any Service Recipient shall not infringe the, including any Intellectual Property Rights, of any third parties; and

shall indemnify the Customer and any Service Recipient(s) in full against all liabilities, costs, expenses, damages and losses (including any direct, indirect or consequential losses, loss of profit, loss of reputation and all interest, penalties and legal costs (calculated on a full indemnity basis) and all other professional costs and expenses) suffered or incurred by the Customer and any Service Recipient(s) arising out of or in connection with any claim brought against the Customer and/or any Service Recipient(s), their agents, subcontractors or consultants as a result of any breach or alleged breach by Supplier of any Applicable Laws or of this Agreement.
Insurance

The Supplier shall maintain in force, with a reputable insurance company, professional indemnity insurance at the amount set out in the Statement of Work or, where no such amount is stated, at an amount appropriate to the Supplier’s liability under this Agreement and shall, on the Customer's request, produce both the insurance certificate giving details of cover and the receipt for the current year's premium.
Compliance with laws and policies
In performing their respective obligations under the Agreement, both parties shall comply with the Applicable Laws.
Changes to the Services (or to how they are carried out) which are required as a result of changes to the Applicable Laws shall be agreed in the Statement of Work.
Data protection
The parties shall comply with the data protection obligations set out in Schedule 3 (Data Protection) or, where relevant, any separate data processing agreement agreed between the parties.
Confidentiality

Each party undertakes that it shall not at any time disclose to any person any confidential information concerning the business, affairs, customers, clients or suppliers of the other party or of any member of the group of companies to which the other party belongs, except as permitted by section12.2.
Each party may disclose the other party's confidential information:

to its employees, officers, representatives, contractors, subcontractors or advisers who need to know such information for the purposes of exercising the party's rights or carrying out its obligations under or in connection with the Agreement. Each party shall ensure that its employees, officers, representatives, contractors, subcontractors or advisers to whom it discloses the other party's confidential information comply with this section12; and
as may be required by law, a court of competent jurisdiction or any governmental or regulatory authority.
No party shall use any other party's confidential information for any purpose other than to exercise its rights and perform its obligations under or in connection with the Agreement.
The Supplier shall procure that each Supplier Personnel shall comply with the requirements of this clause.
Liability

References to liability in this section 13 include every kind of liability arising under or in connection with the Agreement including but not limited to liability in contract, tort (including negligence), misrepresentation, restitution or otherwise.
Nothing in the Agreement shall limits any liability for:
breach of any indemnity under the Agreement;
death or personal injury caused by negligence;
fraud or fraudulent misrepresentation; and
breach of the terms implied by section 2 of the Supply of Goods and Services Act 1982 (title and quiet possession); and
any other liability which cannot legally be limited.

Subject to section 13.2, each party’s total liability for all other loss or damage shall not exceed the total Charges paid to the Supplier under the relevant Statement(s) of Work in the 12 month period leading up to the breach giving rise to the liability.
Termination

Without affecting any other right or remedy available to it, the Customer may terminate the Agreement and/or any or all Statements of Work with immediate effect by giving written notice to the other party if:

the Supplier commits a material breach of any term of the Agreement or any Statement of Work and (if such breach is remediable) fails to remedy that breach within a period of 30 days after being notified in writing to do so;
the Supplier commits any breach of section 12 (Confidentiality); or
the Supplier or an Supplier Personnel, in the judgement of the Customer or any Service Recipient(s):

is unable to, fails, is unwilling to, or refuses to provide adequately the Services reasonably and properly required pursuant to any Statement of Work including, without limitation, in accordance with any agreed timetable;
commits any act of fraud or dishonesty, whether relating to the Customer or any Service Recipient(s) or otherwise, or;

is responsible for any act or omission which in the opinion of the Customer or any Service Recipient(s) brings or is likely to bring the Supplier, the Customer and/or any Service Recipient(s), into disrepute or is materially adverse to the interests of the Customer and/or any Service Recipient(s); or

the Supplier is unable to pay its debts as they fall due or threaten to suffer any resolution to wind up its business or enter into involuntary or compulsory liquidation or have an administrator, administrative receiver or any analogous officer appointed over all or part of its assets; or
the Supplier suspends or ceases, or threatens to suspend or cease, carrying on all or a substantial part of its business; or
the Supplier's financial position deteriorates so far as to reasonably justify the opinion that its ability to give effect to the terms of the Agreement is in jeopardy; or
there is a change of control of the Supplier.
Except as expressly stated otherwise in the Statement of Work, the Customer may terminate a Statement of Work by giving the Supplier 30 days’ written notice.
Effect of termination
The termination of the Agreement by itself shall not automatically terminate any Statement of Work which has not been completed.
The termination of an individual Statement of Work shall not automatically terminate any other Statement of Work or the Agreement.
On termination or expiry of the Agreement for whatever reason:

if any Services under any Statements of Work have not been completed at that date, any provisions of the Agreement which may be relevant to the performance of such Statement of Work shall survive for the term of such Statement of Work until the Statement of Work has been completed; and

the Customer may at its option terminate any and all Statements of Work which have not been completed at the time of termination of the Agreement or at any time thereafter by notice in writing with immediate effect.
Upon termination of any Statement of Work for whatever reason:

the Supplier shall deliver (and shall procure that each Supplier Personnel delivers) to the Customer and any Service Recipient(s) all information provided to the Supplier or to the Supplier Personnel by the Customer or the Service Recipient(s), as relevant, (Service Information) or created as part of the Services under such Statement of Work, including all documents, papers, notes, working papers, manuscripts and typescripts, computer disks and tapes, materials, equipment, technical information and data, files, reports and any other property or Confidential Information belonging to the Customer or any Service Recipient(s);

the Supplier shall delete and shall procure that each Supplier Personnel deletes any Service Information on any IT equipment controlled or used by the Supplier or such Supplier Personnel and shall return in good working order and condition any equipment owned by the Customer or any Service Recipient(s) which may be in the Supplier's or any Supplier Personnel’s possession;

the Supplier shall, if so requested by the Customer, provide all assistance reasonably required by the Customer to facilitate the smooth transition of the Works to the Customer or any replacement supplier appointed by it;

no further payment will be made by the Customer to the Supplier for Services performed by the Supplier under the Statement of Work in question, save that the Customer shall pay the Supplier for Services which, in the reasonable judgement of the Customer, have been performed satisfactorily and/or Deliverables which have been accepted by the Customer (or the Service Recipient(s), where relevant) (on a pro rata basis where appropriate).  Notwithstanding the foregoing the Customer may, at its sole option, reclaim and recover any advance payments made to the Supplier in relation to such Statement of Work, or any Charges paid for Deliverables which have subsequently been rejected or cancelled or Services which have not, in the reasonable judgement of the Customer, been satisfactorily performed as of the date of termination.
Survival

On termination or expiry of the Agreement and/or any Statement of Work any provision of the Agreement and/or Statement of Work that expressly or by implication is intended to come into or continue in force on or after such termination or expiry shall remain in full force and effect.

Termination or expiry of the Agreement and/or any Statement of Work shall not affect any rights, remedies, obligations or liabilities of the parties that have accrued up to the date of termination or expiry, including the right to claim damages in respect of any breach which existed at or before the date of termination or expiry.
Force majeure

Neither party shall be in breach of the Agreement or a Statement of Work nor liable for delay in performing, or failure to perform, any of its obligations under the Agreement or Statement of Work if such delay or failure result from events, circumstances or causes beyond its reasonable control.
Assignment and other dealings

The Agreement is personal to the Supplier and the Supplier shall not assign, transfer, mortgage, charge, subcontract, delegate, declare a trust over or deal in any other manner with any of its rights and obligations under the Agreement.
The Customer may at any time assign, transfer, charge, subcontract, declare a trust over or deal in any other manner with any or all of its rights under the Agreement.
Variation

Subject to section 2 (Statements of Work), no variation of the Agreement (including any Statement of Work) shall be effective unless it is in writing and signed by the parties (or their authorised representatives).
Waiver
A waiver of any right or remedy under the Agreement or by law is only effective if given in writing and shall not be deemed a waiver of any subsequent right or remedy.

A failure or delay by a party to exercise any right or remedy provided under the Agreement or by law shall not constitute a waiver of that or any other right or remedy, nor shall it prevent or restrict any further exercise of that or any other right or remedy. No single or partial exercise of any right or remedy provided under the Agreement or by law shall prevent or restrict the further exercise of that or any other right or remedy.

A party that waives a right or remedy provided under the Agreement or by law in relation to one party, or takes or fails to take any action against that party, does not affect its rights in relation to any other party.
Rights and remedies
The rights and remedies provided under the Agreement are in addition to, and not exclusive of, any rights or remedies provided by law.
Severance

If any provision or part-provision of the Agreement is or becomes invalid, illegal or unenforceable, it shall be deemed deleted, but that shall not affect the validity and enforceability of the rest of the Agreement.

If any provision or part-provision of the Agreement is deemed deleted under section 22.1 the parties shall negotiate in good faith to agree a replacement provision that, to the greatest extent possible, achieves the intended commercial result of the original provision.
Entire agreement

The Agreement constitutes the entire agreement between the parties and supersedes and extinguishes all previous agreements, promises, assurances, warranties, representations and understandings between them, whether written or oral, relating to its subject matter.

Each party agrees that it shall have no remedies in respect of any statement, representation, assurance or warranty (whether made innocently or negligently) that is not set out in the Agreement. Each party agrees that it shall have no claim for innocent or negligent misrepresentation based on any statement in the Agreement.
Conflict
If there is an inconsistency between any of the provisions of the Agreement and the provisions of a Statement of Work, the Statement of Work shall prevail.
No partnership or agency

The relationship of the Supplier (and, where relevant, any Supplier Personnel) to the Customer and any Service Recipient(s) shall be that of independent contractor and nothing in this Agreement or any Statement of Work shall render it (nor any Supplier Personnel) an employee, worker, agent, representative or partner of the Customer or any Service Recipient(s) and the Supplier shall not, and shall procure that no Supplier Personnel shall, hold itself out as such.

Unless they have been specifically authorised to do so by the Customer or any Service Recipient(s) in writing, neither the Supplier nor any Supplier Personnel shall have any authority to incur any expenditure in the name of or for the account of the Customer or the Service Recipient(s), or to bind or otherwise create or assume any obligation for or on behalf of the Customer or the Service Recipient(s) and the Supplier shall not hold itself out as such and shall procure that no Supplier Personnel shall hold themselves out as such.

Nothing in the Agreement is intended to, or shall be deemed to, establish any partnership or joint venture between any of the parties, constitute any party the agent of another party, or authorise any party to make or enter into any commitments for or on behalf of any other party.
Each party confirms it is acting on its own behalf and not for the benefit of any other person.

The Agreement (including all Statements of Work) constitutes a contract for the provision of services and not a contract of employment and accordingly the Supplier shall be fully responsible for and hereby indemnifies the Customer and any Service Recipient(s) against:

Schedule 3 - Data Protection
In this Schedule, the following definitions and rules of interpretation shall apply:
The terms controller, processor, data subject, personal data, personal data breach and processing shall have the meaning given to them in the UK GDPR.

Applicable Data Protection Laws: means all applicable data protection and privacy and regulatory requirements in force from time to time which apply to a party relating to the protection and use of personal data (including, without limitation, the privacy of electronic communications) including, without limitation, the UK GDPR and the EU GDPR.
Customer Personal Data: means any personal data which the Supplier processes in connection with the Agreement in the capacity of a processor or sub-processor appointed by the Customer.
EU GDPR: means the General Data Protection Regulation ((EU) 2016/679).
Purpose: means the purposes for which the Customer Personal Data is processed, as set out in paragraph 7.1 of this Schedule.
UK GDPR: has the meaning given to it in the Data Protection Act 2018.
A reference to an Annex means an Annex of this Schedule.

Both parties will comply with all applicable requirements of Applicable Data Protection Laws. This Schedule is in addition to, and does not relieve, remove or replace, a party's obligations or rights under Applicable Data Protection Laws.
The parties have determined that, for the purposes of Applicable Data Protection Laws the Supplier shall process the personal data set out in Annex 1 in the capacity of:
a processor on behalf of the Customer (where the Customer is the controller); or
a sub-processor where the Customer acts as a processor on behalf of the Customer’s own customer(s) and engages the Supplier as a sub-processor.
Should the determination in paragraph 3 change, then each party shall work together in good faith to make any changes which are necessary to this Schedule or Annex 1.

In relation to the Customer Personal Data, Annex 1 sets out the scope, nature and purpose of processing by the Supplier, the duration of the processing and the types of personal data and categories of data subject.  These details may be amended in a Statement of Work in relation to the relevant Services.
Without prejudice to paragraph 2, the Supplier shall, in relation to Customer Personal Data:

process that Customer Personal Data only on the documented instructions of the Customer, which shall be to process the Customer Personal Data for the purposes set out in Annex 1 as amended by the relevant Statement of Work, unless the Supplier is required by Applicable Laws to otherwise process that Customer Personal Data. Where the Supplier is relying on Applicable Laws as the basis for processing Customer Processor Data, the Supplier shall notify the Customer of this before performing the processing required by the Applicable Laws unless those Applicable Laws prohibit the Supplier from so notifying the Customer on important grounds of public interest. The Supplier shall inform the Customer if, in the opinion of the Supplier, the instructions of the Customer infringe Applicable Data Protection Laws;

implement appropriate technical and organisational measures to protect against unauthorised or unlawful processing of Customer Personal Data and against accidental loss or destruction of, or damage to, Customer Personal Data, including inter alia as appropriate:
the pseudonymisation and encryption of Customer Personal Data;
the ability to ensure the ongoing confidentiality, integrity, availability and resilience of processing systems and services;
the ability to restore the availability and access to Customer Personal Data in a timely manner in the event of a physical or technical incident; and
a process for regularly testing, assessing and evaluating the effectiveness of technical and organisational measures for ensuring the security of the processing.

In assessing the appropriate level of security the Supplier shall take into account in particular of the risks that are presented by the processing, in particular from accidental or unlawful destruction, loss, alteration, unauthorised disclosure of, or access to Customer Personal Data transmitted, stored or otherwise processed.
ensure that any Supplier Personnel who have access to and/or process personal data are obliged to keep the personal data confidential;

promptly assist the Customer, at the Supplier's expense, in responding to any request from a data subject and in ensuring compliance with the Customer's obligations under Applicable Data Protection Laws with respect to security, breach notifications, impact assessments and consultations with any supervisory authorities or other regulators, any agreements between the Customer and its customers and, in particular, the Supplier shall promptly notify the Customer if it receives any complaint, notice or communication (whether from any data subject, supervisory authority or other third party) which relates to processing of Customer Personal Data;

notify the Customer without undue delay (and no later than 24 hours) after becoming aware of a personal data breach and on suspecting the same, the Supplier shall promptly conduct an initial assessment to determine, with a reasonable degree of certainty, whether the event or incident qualifies for notification to the Customer under this paragraph and shall provide a copy of this initial assessment along with such notification;

at the written direction of the Customer, delete or return to the Customer all Customer Personal Data on termination or expiry of the agreement, and certify to the Customer in writing it has done so, unless the Supplier is required by Applicable Law to continue to process that Customer Personal Data, in which case the Supplier shall promptly notify the Customer, in writing, of what that Applicable Law is and shall only be permitted to process that Customer Personal Data for the specific purpose so-notified, and all other requirements set out in this Schedule shall continue to apply to such Customer Personal Data notwithstanding the termination or expiry of this agreement for as long as such Customer Personal Data is processed by the Supplier. For the purposes of this paragraph the obligation to "delete" data includes the obligation to delete data from back-up systems as well as live systems; and

maintain adequate records, and, on the Customer's request, make available such information as the Customer may reasonably request, and allow for and submit its premises and operations to audits, including inspections, by the Customer or the Customer's designated auditor, to demonstrate its compliance with Applicable Data Protection Laws and this Schedule.

The Supplier shall not, without the prior written consent of the Customer (and in any event subject to the Supplier providing the Customer with reasonable evidence that such activity is being undertaking in full compliance with Applicable Data Protection Laws):
appoint or replace (or change the terms of the appointment of) any other processor in relation to Customer Personal Data or transfer any Customer Personal Data to the same; or

carry out, via itself or via any other processor, any processing of Customer Personal Data, or transfer any Customer Personal Data, outside of the UK, including processing Customer Personal Data on equipment situated outside of the UK.

Where the Customer provides written consent under paragraph 7, the Supplier shall ensure that the terms on which it appoints such processors are consistent with the obligations imposed on the Supplier in this Schedule and shall remain responsible for the acts and omission of any such processor as if they were the acts and omissions of the Supplier.
